      children: "Egypt’s status as a bastion of antique cultural achievements underlies much of the drive behind Shawky’s work. His three-part work, Al Araba Al Madfuna (2012-2016), features children replaying myths, legends, and histories of the past, hinting at the importance of oral history in Arab tradition and the power of narrative to shape our perceptions and actions from a young age. He was inspired by his own touristic journey along the Nile in his home country, from his hometown of Alexandria to the town of El Araba El Madfuna."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Much of Shawky’s art originates with research. His most famous work, Cabaret Crusades (2010),  was inspired by the book The Crusades Through Arab Eyes by Amin Maalouf. The films recount the story of the Crusades, a series of military expeditions between 1095 and 1291 led by the Catholic Church into the Holy Land to wrest Jerusalem from Islamic rule. Reframing the Crusades through an Arab lens, Shawky sheds light on the problematic nature of Euro-centric historiography that privileges one version of the past over another. The “actors” take the form of 200-year-old marionettes that speak in classical Arabic. Their strings are visible as they move throughout the landscape, a choice that Shawky has described as a “metaphor for manipulation.”"
    }), "\n", _jsxs(_components.p, {
      children: ["At the 2024 edition of the famed Venice Biennale, a foremost platform for contemporary art around the world, Shawky was selected by the government to represent Egypt. On the condition that the government could not censor his work, he chose to craft his Egyptian Pavilion to center a new 45-minute video installation entitled ", _jsx(_components.a, {
