      children: "Egyptian artist Ghada Amer attended art school in France, where she had lived since her preteen years. Over the course of her bachelors and masters in the 1980s, she discovered that she was to be excluded from painting class because she was a woman, propelling the feminist turn that much of her work would take. Amer distinctively combines paint and thread to explore femininity and sexuality, often portraying women in erotic positions derived from pornography magazines. Amer’s identity as an (Egyptian) (Arab) (international) woman permeates her work as she foregrounds female subjectivity and the female gaze in a deliberately feminist practice."
