      children: "Beginning in the 1990s, Amer incorporated embroidery into her pieces to create textural two-dimensional works. The first such work, Cinque femmes au travail (1991), used the simple threads to show women in domestic settings cleaning, cooking, and caring for children, thus deliberately playing on the stereotypes of women’s work. The tapestries, however, include only four women. The fifth is understood to be the artist, whose women’s work is unpictured but present in the objects’ material being. Later works feature looser threads, chaotic lines, and painted marks to create visual landscapes evoking the complexity of womanhood. The splattered paint across her later works like Red Diagonals (2000) references the history of Abstract Expressionism, a movement associated with mid-century masculinity. Throughout her works, Amer thus complicates the prescriptive gender binary she has seen in her many homes across the world."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Amer first learned to sew and embroider from her mother and grandmother, who often made their own clothes. In the 1980s during her trips back to Cairo with her family, she witnessed women’s behavior in Egypt changed as more adopted the practice of veiling, alongside the rise of the conservative religious Muslim Brotherhood. Art historian Chika Okeke-Agulu has argued that her focus on the undressed female body, autoeroticism, and homosexuality derives from and is a response to these early experiences in Egypt. Her embroidery holistically addresses the iterations of femininity and forms of oppression that she has witnessed across the many cultural spaces she moves between, from Egypt to France to the United States."
